Panic's Limit
Copenhagen — We often hear that the world as we know it will face the end, and the usual explanation is ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Club of Rome released the seminal work "The Limits to Growth" over forty years ago, its core idea has been with us all along.
But time is not forgiving.
The 1972 "Limits to Growth" warned humanity that catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, after that we saw financial panic, but no real shortages or production collapse.
On the contrary, the resources created by human genius are more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
But the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still stands: we continue a trend, preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues, while neglecting the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, the optimism about technology faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society plunged into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited public fear of pollution and also sparked the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 book "The Population Bomb" made everything clear.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were pessimistic.
The intention of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people consume too much.
Even if our genius buys us some time, we will eventually destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than now.
This view is still resonating today, despite being completely wrong.
For example, the authors of The Limits to Growth predicted that the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, although commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of their levels from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dentistry materials, and thermometers, and by the year 2000, mercury consumption had declined by 98%, and its price had dropped by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to run out by 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, their reserves are higher than in 1970, despite our greatly increased consumption.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas resources in the United States and cut prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries seeing an increase of 24 times.
The reason "The Limits to Growth" was wrong is because the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has slowed since the 1960s.
The food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being used, and there are an additional 2.7 billion hectares in reserve).
The rate of malnutrition has been reduced by more than half, from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not stopped us.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where there was no air pollution from suspended particles, and everyone was happy as farmers, while in the future, heating chimneys would make it impossible to breathe. Reality is the complete opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people — equivalent to one in every 500 people — died from air pollution each year, most of it from indoor air pollution.
Now, the ratio has dropped to one death in every 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths caused by pollution is still higher than that from malaria, the mortality rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Nevertheless, the notion cultivated by The Limits to Growth continues to influence the thinking of the public and the elites.
Taking recycling, for example, it is usually just a gesture that makes people feel better, costing a lot to the environment but yielding little.
For instance, paper is usually sourced from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The programs related to paper recycling and government subsidies lead to low-quality paper, and what they protect are resources that are not actually threatened.
Similarly, concerns about overpopulation have led to self-destructive policies, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization.
Furthermore, although pesticides and other pollutants are believed to kill half of humanity, effective pesticide regulation results in only 20 deaths per year in the United States, while pesticide use has created more affordable and abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — — a movement driven by pesticide panic — — would add an additional $100 billion annually to the cost in the United States.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland — — half the size of modern-day California — — would be needed.
Rising prices will lead to a decline in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health impacts (including an increase of hundreds of thousands of cancer deaths annually).
Being obsessed with dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, yet easily curable diseases still cause 15 million deaths each year — equivalent to a quarter of total deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most can afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of people in poverty by nearly a billion.
This has resulted in widespread improvements in health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The forty years since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring more than 100 trillion dollars in benefits by the end of this century, far surpassing the benefits of the timid "feel-good" policies fueled by fear.
But this requires abandoning the anti-growth mindset and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
